The "Pro" Solution: We will implement Multi-Select (Shift+Click) and "Copy as File" (Ctrl+C).

Why: This allows users to select 50 songs, hit Ctrl+C, and then Paste them directly into a Folder, Premiere Pro, or FL Studio. It mimics Drag-and-Drop behavior natively without breaking the app.

Here is the 2-step plan to add this "Power User" functionality.

Step 1: Enable Batch Selection (Shift/Ctrl Click)
We need to rewrite the click logic in library_tab.py to handle multiple rows.

The Prompt:

Copy and paste this:

"I need to add Multi-Select (Batch Actions) to my Library. Please modify library_tab.py.

1. Selection State:

Update LibraryRow: Add a set_selected(bool) method.

Style: If selected, change background to the Theme's 'Hover Color' (or Blue). If deselected, revert to transparent/gray.

2. The Controller (LibraryTab):

Add self.selected_rows = [].

Click Logic:

Click: Deselect all others, select this one.

Ctrl+Click: Toggle selection of this row; keep others.

Shift+Click: Select all rows between the last selected row and this one.

3. Context Menu Update:

Update the Right-Click menu to act on All Selected Rows.

Batch Delete: 'Delete 5 selected items?'

Batch Playlist: 'Add 5 items to Playlist...'

4. Keyboard Shortcuts:

Bind Ctrl+A to 'Select All'.

Bind Escape to 'Deselect All'."

Step 2: "Copy to DAW" (The Export Feature)
Now that we can select 50 songs, we need to move them. We will use the Windows Clipboard (CF_HDROP) so the user can Paste them anywhere.

The Prompt:

Copy and paste this:

"I need to implement Batch Export via the Clipboard.

1. Install Dependency:

I will install pywin32 (pip install pywin32). Please import win32clipboard and win32con.

2. The 'Copy Files' Function:

Create a function copy_selection_to_clipboard() in library_tab.py.

Logic:

Get the file paths of all self.selected_rows.

Use win32clipboard to open the clipboard.

Set the clipboard data format to CF_HDROP (this is the Windows standard for 'File Drop').

This allows me to Paste the songs directly into Windows Explorer, FL Studio, or Premiere.

3. Triggers:

Bind Ctrl+C to trigger this function.

Add 'Copy Files' to the Right-Click Context Menu.

Show a small 'Copied 5 files to clipboard' toast notification."

Why this is better than "Drag and Drop"
Reliability: Dragging out of Tkinter is buggy and often crashes. Copy/Paste works 100% of the time.

Speed: It is faster to Ctrl+A -> Ctrl+C -> Alt+Tab -> Ctrl+V than to drag 2,000 pixels across screens.

Compatibility: Every DAW supports "Paste Audio Files."